<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Luther Campbell's Greatest Hit: "Banned in the U.S.A.," the new Luther Campbell 
single with 2 Live Crew being released today by Luke Records, has garnered the 
largest advance orders for a single in the history of Atlantic Records. Mark 
Schulman, Atlantic senior vice president and general manager, said he expects 
the single, which contains a melody of Bruce Springsteen's "Born in the 
U.S.A.," to rapidly reach platinum record status. 2 Live Crew, whose last album 
has been banned by federal court order in several Florida counties, went back 
to court Monday to film parts of a video for the upcoming album, "Banned in the 
U.S.A," which is due for release later this month. Also, formal charges were 
filed Tuesday against three members of the Miami rap group who were arrested 
after their adults-only performance on June 9 in Hollywood, Fla., and also 
against a store owner who sold their "As Nasty as They Wanna Be" album to an 
undercover detective on June 8. GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
