<HEADLINE>
<P>
"...AND THE ROCKETS' RED GLARE, THE BOMBS BURSTING IN AIR..."; 
</P>
<P>
HOW FIREWORKS GET THEIR COLORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fireworks' color palette is created by using precise amounts of chemicals 
mixed with the explosives. Blues, for example, are obtained by using copper, 
Strontium salts make the red colors, calcium makes orange and sodium makes 
yellow. Since World War II, organic compounds of chlorine have been mixed with 
the explosive to make the color burn brighter. The sparkling effects are 
created by using metals, such as iron or magnesium, which burn brightly when 
placed in an explosive mixture. 
</P>
<P>
Source: Collier's Encyclopedia 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
